# Consensus-atomic cutovers

`06-branching.mdc`'s 5-working-day / 10-commit guidance is a defense
against unreviewable PRs accumulating, and the default is that every
substantive change splits to land that way. A small number of PRs
genuinely cannot — specifically, PRs whose work would leave the
chain in a non-canonical state at any intermediate split point,
because validators reach different conclusions about the same
block depending on which subset of the cutover they have applied.

This rule names that exception class so the carve-out is auditable
mechanically against named criteria, not against precedent erosion
("we did it for X, can we do it for Y?"). Per
`21-reversion-clause-discipline.mdc`'s named-criteria principle, the
test is "does this PR meet criteria 1–4?", not "is this case
analogous to a previous case?"

## Scope

This rule defines when a PR may exceed `06-branching.mdc`'s size
and atomicity guidance. It does not relax any other discipline:
the standard reviewer rigor, commit-message discipline
(`90-commits.mdc`), test-gate requirements, and design-doc-first
ordering (`05-system-thinking.mdc`) all still apply. The
exception modifies only the splitting requirement, and only when
all four criteria below are met.

## When this exception applies

All four criteria must be met. Each is independently testable;
"arguable" does not satisfy a criterion.

1. **Consensus-rule boundary.** The PR changes behavior that all
   correctly-implementing nodes must reproduce byte-identically on
   the same input. Internal refactors that preserve consensus
   behavior do not qualify. Logging changes, RPC formatting
   adjustments, internal cache restructurings, function-name
   renames, and file reorganizations of consensus code that
   preserve the rule do **not** qualify; only changes to the
   rule itself (values, computation, validation logic) do.

2. **Indivisible under flag decomposition.** This criterion is
   met whenever criterion 1 is met. The reason is structural,
   not contingent: for a consensus-rule change, flag
   decomposition is **structurally inapplicable**, not "tried
   and found wanting."

   A flag decomposition only counts as consensus-safe if **both
   flag states are simultaneously valid** — i.e., the flag is
   a daemon-side preference that does not affect consensus
   output. Build-system flags (which FFI to link), performance-
   tuning flags (which cache strategy), and instrumentation
   flags (which trace level) qualify; they route the
   implementation without changing the output that consensus
   compares.

   For a **consensus rule**, simultaneous-validity of both
   states is impossible by definition: correctly-implementing
   nodes must produce byte-identical output on the same input,
   so a flag that gates consensus behavior would have to
   dispatch identically regardless of state, which means it
   doesn't gate consensus behavior at all. It is then one of
   the non-consensus flag classes above, and the change it
   gates does not satisfy criterion 1.

   Equivalently: the only "flag" that gates consensus behavior
   in a coordinated way is the chain height at which a hard-fork
   activates — but Shekyl's pre-genesis posture per
   `60-no-monero-legacy.mdc` explicitly rejects in-Shekyl
   version-dispatch, and post-genesis hard-fork activations are
   themselves the consensus event the PR ratifies. Either way,
   the "flag" is not a decomposition that produces
   consensus-safe intermediates at every commit; it *is* the
   atomicity that criterion 2 names.

   Therefore: a PR that meets criterion 1 (genuinely changes
   consensus output) automatically meets criterion 2. A PR
   that *appears* to meet criterion 1 but is actually
   flag-decomposable into consensus-safe intermediates was not
   a consensus-rule change to begin with; criterion 1 fails,
   the exception does not apply, and the PR splits per
   `06-branching.mdc`. This shape closes the loophole where a
   PR author argues "yes, this is a consensus change, but
   splitting would be inconvenient" — there is no such PR;
   either the change affects consensus output (criterion 1 +
   2 both met) or it does not (neither met).

3. **Surface enumerated in advance, with evidence.** The PR
   description contains a grep-result-derived enumeration of
   every consensus-affecting symbol, file, and constant being
   changed. The enumeration is the audit evidence that
   completeness is checkable; "I'll find them as I touch each
   file" does not satisfy this criterion. The grep result is
   pasted into the PR description (or linked to a design-doc
   section that contains it) so the reviewer can verify
   completeness against the diff mechanically.

   The grep is **run against the PR's base commit** (the
   `dev` SHA the PR branches from, recorded in the PR
   description as `Base commit: <sha>`) and **timestamped**
   at PR-open. Reviewers re-run the same grep against the same
   base commit to verify the enumeration has not shifted since
   the PR was opened. A grep run weeks before PR-open and
   pasted in without a base-commit anchor does not satisfy
   this criterion: the audit purpose is that the surface is
   reproducible, not that the PR author once saw it.

4. **Disposition documented in PR, with reversibility plan.**
   The PR description must contain each of the following.
   Sub-clauses 4.3 and 4.4 are themselves load-bearing
   discipline, not paperwork; their accuracy is part of what
   reviewers verify.

   4.1. **Rule citation.** The PR cites this rule by name
   (`07-consensus-atomic-cutovers.mdc`) in the description.
   Retroactive citation does not satisfy 4.1 (see "What this
   exception is not" below).

   4.2. **Per-criterion justification.** The PR lists which
   of criteria 1–4 are met with one sentence per criterion
   explaining the justification. Criterion 4's entry is the
   sub-clause structure itself.

   4.3. **Reviewer-map section.** The PR description
   distinguishes consensus-affecting changes (files X, Y, Z;
   lines A–B in each) from mechanical changes (call-site
   rewires, no logic change) from deletions (files removed
   wholesale). The map lets a reviewer prioritize attention
   without spelunking the diff. **Enforcement:** the map's
   accuracy is itself a review item. A reviewer who finds
   substantive consensus changes outside the map's
   "consensus-affecting" subsection has identified a
   map-failure, which is grounds for rejecting the PR
   (not for amending the map mid-review). "The map missed
   one" is a sign the criterion-3 enumeration was incomplete;
   the response is to re-open the PR with a corrected
   enumeration, not to patch the map.

   4.4. **Rollback procedure.** The PR description names the
   specific files and changes that constitute reversion if
   consensus breaks post-merge. "We'd revert the commit" is
   not a rollback procedure — it's the absence of one. The
   procedure is written in advance so a panicked rollback
   isn't reconstructing it in real time. **Enforcement:** the
   procedure must be executable as-written by a reviewer who
   has not seen the PR before. A rollback procedure that
   requires the original author's tacit knowledge to apply
   has not satisfied 4.4; the procedure is then itself
   grounds for rejecting the PR.

## What this exception is not

The criteria above are the test. The justifications below are
**explicitly not** criteria; a PR citing this rule must not be
relying on any of them:

- **Convenience.** "This is easier as one PR" is not a
  criterion. Easier-than-splitting is the default expectation
  that `06-branching.mdc` rejects.
- **Velocity.** "Splitting would slow down the migration" is
  not a criterion. Migrations are slow by design; the discipline
  is what makes them bisectable later.
- **Reviewer bandwidth.** "We'd waste reviewer time on three
  PRs" is not a criterion. The exception trades reviewability
  for atomicity; criterion 4's reviewer-map is the
  compensating discipline, not "skip the reviewer's bandwidth
  cost."
- **Retroactive citation.** A PR that did not cite this rule
  in its initial description **cannot** invoke the exception
  later. The disposition is named at PR open; mid-review
  invocation is reactive scope expansion, which the rule does
  not authorize.

## Compensating discipline when the exception is invoked

The exception trades reviewability-cost for atomicity-correctness.
Most of the per-criterion enforcement is now in-line with the
criteria (sub-clauses 4.3 and 4.4 in particular). One additional
discipline cuts across the criteria:

- **Scope-creep loses the exception.** Criterion 3's
  grep-anchored enumeration is the scope-bounding artifact. A
  PR that grows beyond the enumerated surface during review
  **loses the exception** and must be re-opened against the
  standard size/atomicity guidance — scope creep within an
  exception-invoking PR is grounds for rejecting the PR, not
  for re-arguing the exception. "We discovered we need to
  touch one more file" is exactly the failure mode the
  exception was designed to constrain.

## History of application

The exception class is auditable by enumeration of past
invocations. Each invocation cites this rule, demonstrates
the four criteria are met, and links here. Approved
invocations:

- **LWMA-1 Phase 4** (`docs/design/DAA_LWMA1_PLAN.md` Phase 4;
  landed on `dev` 2026-05-18 as PR #53 merge commit
  `ef6f6bb66871ad6547ae92591ecabf43f9426f0b`; pre-merge branch tip
  archived as tag `archive/feat-daa-lwma1-phase4-2026-05-19` at
  `e1384eac0`; the eleven-commit decomposition disposed in
  `docs/design/DAA_LWMA1_PHASE4_PREFLIGHT.md` §18).
  Difficulty-algorithm cutover from CryptoNote
  cut-windowed-average to LWMA-1, paired with FTL and MTP
  value changes. The FTL (`7200 → 540`) and MTP (`60 → 11`)
  value changes are consensus-rule constants; both
  validating nodes have to agree on the same FTL and MTP
  values at the same height, and there is no
  simultaneously-valid flag decomposition (per criterion 2)
  that produces a consensus-safe intermediate. Criteria 1
  (consensus-rule boundary: FTL/MTP/algorithm), 2 (no
  simultaneously-valid flag decomposition exists for any of
  the three), 3 (enumerated in advance: `DAA_LWMA1.md`
  §§9.4–9.7, with the Phase 4 implementation amendments
  recorded in `DAA_LWMA1_PLAN.md` "Phase 4 implementation
  drift findings" section), and 4 (disposition: the Phase 4 PR
  description cited this rule and contained the
  sub-clause-4.1–4.4 artifacts; the rollback procedure was
  "revert the merge commit on `dev`" because the cutover was
  atomic and reversion is single-commit). The five-commit
  consensus-rule cluster (commits 3–5: DAA rewires, FTL
  rewires, MTP rewires; commits 7–8: `#define` deletions and
  surgical `next_difficulty` deletion) is the reviewer-map
  "consensus-affecting" subsection; commits 1, 2, 6, 9, 10,
  and 11 are the mechanical / new-artifact / deletion shape
  per sub-clause 4.3.

  *In-flight discipline lesson.* Seven implementation drift
  findings (F1–F7, recorded in `DAA_LWMA1_PLAN.md` "Phase 4
  implementation drift findings") surfaced during the PR.
  F1, F6, and F7 are the load-bearing class: each was a
  case where the pre-flight specified wholesale deletion
  and implementation revealed surgical deletion was the
  correct shape (the file contained both load-bearing and
  deletion-target code; the pre-flight didn't distinguish).
  The pre-flight §18 "implementation-time drift" policy
  absorbed these without triggering scope-creep-loses-the-
  exception per sub-clause 4-criterion-3, because each
  finding *narrowed* scope rather than expanding it. The
  pattern argues for a forward-template item in this rule
  (future pre-flights for consensus-atomic cutovers should
  distinguish "delete the file" from "delete these specific
  symbols in the file" at pre-flight time, not at
  implementation time); landed under §18 here so future
  invocations inherit the lesson without amending the rule.

### Cases that might appear analogous but are not

These cases share surface features with consensus-atomic
cutovers but fail one of the criteria structurally, not
contingently. They are documented so the rule's history
does not read as "exceptions have been rejected before"
(which would invite "we should approve this one since we
rejected that one"); the cases below were never candidates
in the first place.

- **RandomX v2 Phase 3** (`docs/design/RANDOMX_V2_PLAN.md`).
  The algorithm change itself (v1 → v2) does **not** ship
  in Phase 3; it ships in Phase 1's submodule swap. Phase
  3's 3a/3b/3c plan is implementation routing: the FFI
  binding moves from the legacy path to the
  monero-oxide-vendored path, and the algorithm body is
  byte-identical on both sides of the 3a build flag. The
  3a flag is therefore a **build-system / FFI-routing
  flag**, not a consensus flag — both flag states produce
  identical hash outputs because they call the same
  algorithm via different code paths. Criterion 1 is not
  met (no consensus-rule change in Phase 3); the exception
  is **structurally inapplicable**, not "evaluated and
  rejected." Each sub-PR (3a/3b/3c) fits the standard
  `06-branching.mdc` size limit independently.

### Mechanism for future invocations

Future invocations append to this section **as part of the
invoking PR itself**, not after-the-fact. Concretely: the
PR that invokes the exception must include a commit that
adds its own entry to "Approved invocations" above (or, if
review concludes the exception does not apply, to "Cases
that might appear analogous but are not"). The entry is
written by the PR author, reviewed alongside the rest of
the PR, and lands when the PR lands. This makes the audit
trail self-anchoring: a PR cannot invoke the exception
without leaving evidence in this rule's history, and a
reviewer reading the rule months later sees every
invocation that ever cited it.

A PR that invokes the rule but does not include the
history-entry commit fails sub-clause 4.1 (rule citation
is incomplete: the citation must include the history-entry
commit, not just the prose reference).

## Related rules

- **`00-mission.mdc`** — security and quantum resilience are
  preconditions. The exception exists because consensus
  integrity is the security property that flag-decomposable
  splits are designed to preserve in the normal case;
  consensus-atomic cutovers are the cases where atomicity is
  the property and splittability would undermine it.
- **`05-system-thinking.mdc`** — specification first. The
  surface enumerated in advance (criterion 3) is the
  specification-side artifact that the exception requires; an
  unspecified-in-advance PR is not eligible regardless of
  consensus-atomicity.
- **`06-branching.mdc`** — the rule this exception modifies.
  All other branching guidance (no direct commits to `main`,
  no long-lived feature branches, no `dev`-merges-into-feature
  rebases, no force-pushes to `main`/`dev`) is unmodified.
  The exception touches only the 5-day / 10-commit splitting
  guidance.
- **`15-deletion-and-debt.mdc`** — "while we're here" is the
  enemy. The exception is not authorization for unrelated
  changes to ride along with a consensus-atomic cutover;
  scope is the criterion-3-enumerated surface, and "while
  we're here" additions break the exception per criterion 3.
- **`21-reversion-clause-discipline.mdc`** — named-criteria
  principle. The exception's auditability comes from the
  named criteria being mechanically testable, the same
  shape that reversion clauses use for "reject now, reopen
  if X." The exception is the same discipline applied to
  "allow this exception only if conditions 1–4."
- **`90-commits.mdc`** — scope per commit. The exception
  relaxes the *PR* splitting guidance; within the PR,
  commits still respect single-purpose scope per the commit
  rule. A consensus-atomic cutover that is one PR is still
  many commits, each with its own bounded scope.
